## 8. Actions Dropdown & Keyboard Navigation

Located at `/Users/anotonio.silva/antonio/lol/src/components/action_panel/actions_dropdown.tsx` (165 lines)

### State Management
```typescript
const [activeIndex, setActiveIndex] = useState(0);
const dropdownRef = useRef<HTMLDivElement>(null);

useEffect(() => {
  if (open && dropdownRef.current) {
    setActiveIndex(0);
    dropdownRef.current.focus();
  }
}, [open]);
```

### Keyboard Handling
```typescript
function handleKeyDown(e: KeyboardEvent) {
  if (e.key === 'k' && e.metaKey) {
    e.preventDefault();
    e.stopPropagation();
    onClose(); // Close on ⌘K
    return;
  }

  if (e.key === 'Escape') {
    onClose();
    return;
  }

  if (e.key === 'ArrowDown') {
    setActiveIndex(i => (i < actions.length - 1 ? i + 1 : 0)); // Wrap around
    return;
  }

  if (e.key === 'ArrowUp') {
    setActiveIndex(i => (i > 0 ? i - 1 : actions.length - 1)); // Wrap around
    return;
  }

  if (e.key === 'Enter') {
    executeAction(activeIndex);
  }
}
```

### Click Outside Detection
```typescript
useEffect(() => {
  if (!open) return;
  function handleClickOutside(e: MouseEvent) {
    const target = e.target as Node;
    if (dropdownRef.current && !dropdownRef.current.contains(target)) {
      if (triggerRef?.current?.contains(target)) return; // Don't close on trigger
      onClose();
    }
  }
  document.addEventListener('mousedown', handleClickOutside);
  return () => document.removeEventListener('mousedown', handleClickOutside);
}, [open, onClose, triggerRef]);
```

### Scroll into View
```typescript
useEffect(() => {
  if (!open) return;
  const container = dropdownRef.current;
  if (!container) return;

  const activeElement = container.querySelector<HTMLElement>(
    `[data-dropdown-index="${activeIndex}"]`,
  );
  activeElement?.scrollIntoView({ block: 'nearest' });
}, [open, activeIndex]);
```

### Render Pattern
```typescript
if (!open || actions.length === 0) return null;

return (
  <div className="actions-dropdown" ref={dropdownRef} role="menu" tabIndex={-1}>
    {actions.map((action, index) => (
      <button
        id={`action-item-${index}`}
        className={`actions-dropdown__item${index === activeIndex ? ' actions-dropdown__item--active' : ''}`}
        data-dropdown-index={index}
        role="menuitem"
        type="button"
        onClick={() => executeAction(index)}
        onMouseEnter={() => setActiveIndex(index)}
      >
        <span className="actions-dropdown__label">{action.label}</span>
        {action.shortcut && <span className="actions-dropdown__shortcut">{action.shortcut}</span>}
      </button>
    ))}
  </div>
);
```

### Styling Active State
```scss
.actions-dropdown__item {
  transition: background-color $transition-fast ease;

  &:hover,
  &--active {
    background-color: $color-accent;
    color: $color-text-on-accent;

    .actions-dropdown__shortcut .kbd__key {
      background-color: $color-kbd-background-on-accent;
      color: $color-text-on-accent-secondary;
    }
  }

  &:focus-visible {
    outline: 2px solid $color-accent;
    outline-offset: -2px;
  }
}
```

---

## Summary of Key Architectural Decisions

1. **Context for Local State**: List and Grid use context to avoid prop drilling of activeIndex
2. **Ref-based Focus Management**: Dropdowns use refs to manage focus and click detection
3. **Animation States**: Components track `exiting` boolean to trigger exit animations separately
4. **Type Safety**: All data structures have clear TypeScript interfaces
5. **Token-based Design**: Single source of truth for colors, spacing, shadows via SCSS
6. **Keyboard-First**: Every modal and dropdown has full keyboard navigation
7. **Accessibility**: ARIA roles, aria-live regions for toasts, proper focus management
8. **CSS Variables**: Grid uses CSS custom properties for dynamic column count
9. **No CSS-in-JS**: Pure SCSS for styling with proper BEM-lite naming convention
10. **Cleanup in Effects**: All event listeners and timers cleaned up on unmount

This architecture is clean, maintainable, and follows Raycast's design patterns closely. Each component is self-contained with a single SCSS file, making it easy to reason about styling dependencies.

